# Component & Layout Rules

These components are **shared and considered stable**. Reuse them as-is.
Do not restyle, restructure, or "improve" them as a side effect of an
unrelated task. Only change them when the user explicitly asks, and only the
specific thing they ask for — never bundle in extra tweaks.

## Stability contract (do NOT change without explicit instruction)

| Component | File | Locked aspects |
|-----------|------|----------------|
| `TopNav` | `src/components/TopNav.tsx` | DOM order `brand → nav → account`; all three are direct siblings of `.site-header-inner`. Do not re-nest. |
| Brand | `.brand`, `.brand-logo`, `.brand-wordmark` | Logo/wordmark `clamp()` sizing and ratio. |
| Nav links | `.nav-link`, `.nav-link--active` | Padding, color, active state. |
| Account | `.site-account`, `.chip--soon` | "Demo" chip + `LinkButton` "Sign Out" (link-button, **never** a filled button). |
| `LinkButton` | `src/components/LinkButton.tsx` | Renders `.btn.btn--link`. |
| `SiteFooter` | `src/components/SiteFooter.tsx` | Single shared footer in `AppShell`; content + behavior. Never add a second footer. |
| Home widgets | `HeroCard`, `MarketFlowWidget`, `WatchlistWidget`, `Tabs` | Internal markup, content, and visual styling. |

When the user references the Figma wireframes, treat them as **structure only**
— never copy their colors/styling and never change widget content.

## Radius & shape tokens

Corner radii come from a concentric **8 / 6 / 4** scale, capped at 8px. **Never
hardcode a radius** — always use the token, so nested corners stay smaller than
their container:

- `--radius-lg` (8px) — card / large containers (`.hero`, `.panel`).
- `--radius-md` (6px) — sub-cards, inner panels, avatar/badge squircles
  (`.avatar-mark`, `.badge-medallion`, `.member-avatar`).
- `--radius-sm` (4px) — buttons, chips, tabs (`.tab`), inputs, focus rings.

Only non-token exceptions allowed: full pills (`999px`) and circles (`50%`)
where that shape is intended, and thin data-viz bars (`.chart-bar`, 2px).
Nothing may exceed 8px. New components must follow this mapping.

## Selectable card interaction standard (`.select-card` / `.is-selected`)

Every card the user can **pick** — watchlist names (`.watch-item`), strategy
cards (`.strategy-card`), market-flow steps (`.flow-step` once selectable), and
any future selectable card — **must share one** rest / hover / selected
treatment. It lives once in the **"Selectable card interaction standard"** block
in `index.css`. Layout, padding, and content stay per-component; only the
interaction *surface* is shared, so the whole set looks and behaves identically.

| State | Treatment |
|-------|-----------|
| Rest | `1px solid var(--border-soft)` on `var(--surface-2)`, `--radius-md` |
| Hover | border → `var(--border-strong)`, `transform: translateY(-1px)` |
| Selected | gold border `rgb(241 178 74 / 0.55)`, `background: var(--surface-1)`, `box-shadow: var(--shadow-glow)` |
| Focus | global `:focus-visible` gold ring (2px `--accent-strong`) — never re-styled per card |

Rules:

- **Apply, don't reinvent.** Put `.select-card` on the interactive element (the
  card itself, or the wrapper that owns the border) and toggle `.is-selected`
  when chosen. The component keeps only its own layout/typography classes.
- **Mirror the state for a11y.** Reflect selection with `aria-pressed` (single-
  select toggles like the watchlist/strategy lists) or `aria-current` (nav).
- **Never hand-roll** `:hover` / active border + glow on a new selectable card,
  and never fork the values — change them in the shared block so every adopter
  moves together.
- **Current adopters:** `.watch-item`, `.strategy-card`, and `.flow-step` (the
  market-flow steps — the li owns `.select-card` + the border/art; the inner
  `.flow-select` button handles the click + `aria-pressed`).

## App shell (`.app` / `.app-main` / `SiteFooter`)

The shell is `AppShell` → `TopNav` + `.app-main` (the active page) + `SiteFooter`.
It wraps **every authenticated page**, so the header and footer are single shared
instances — never add a page-local header or footer. The scroll model differs by
viewport on purpose:

- **Desktop / tablet (`≥ 768px`)** — `.app` is a fixed-height (`100dvh`) flex
  column with `overflow: hidden`; `.app-main` is the **single scrolling region**
  (`overflow: hidden auto`, `overscroll-behavior-y: contain`). The header and
  footer are pinned chrome (always visible) and the content scrolls between them.
  The **document must never scroll** here (no second scrollbar dragging the
  header/footer): the root is locked to the viewport via
  `@media (min-width: 768px) { html:has(.app), body:has(.app), #root:has(.app) { height: 100%; overflow: hidden } }`.
  Don't put `min-height: 100vh`/`100dvh` on `body` or on a page root — it fights
  `.app`'s `100dvh` and reintroduces the outer scrollbar.
- **Mobile (`≤ 767px`)** — the **whole page scrolls** on every page: `.app` is
  `height: auto; min-height: 100svh; overflow: visible` and `.app-main` is
  `flex: 1 1 auto; overflow: visible`. The header stays sticky at top; the footer
  is end-of-page content that flows **below** the content (scroll to reveal)
  instead of stealing viewport height. Don't reintroduce a fixed shell on mobile.
- Home layers its deck on top of the mobile model (`.app-main:has(.home-page)` is
  content-height + flush tabs); other pages get the standard model for free.
- Applies to the authenticated shell only — never to the login/onboarding screens
  (they render outside `AppShell` and have no footer by design).

### `SiteFooter` (`src/components/SiteFooter.tsx`)

The one and only footer. Rendered once by `AppShell`, so it appears identically on
every page (and any future page that renders in the shell). Content is locked.
Its responsive behavior is the `.site-footer` rule described above — pinned on
desktop/tablet, flowing end-of-page on mobile. Keep all footer changes in this
component + `.site-footer`; never add a second footer.

## Pages — layout & scroll contract (applies to every new page)

A "page" is the component rendered into `.app-main` (see `App.tsx` →
`ActivePage`). New pages inherit the shell's scroll model for free, so they must
**not** fight it:

- **The page is just content.** Render a single root element (convention:
  `<div className="page <name>-page">`) that sizes to its content. Let the shell
  own scrolling — `.app-main` scrolls on desktop/tablet, the page scrolls on
  mobile. A new page needs **no** special height/overflow CSS to scroll.
- **Never create a second scroller for the whole page.** Don't put `100vh` /
  `100dvh` / `min-height: 100vh` or `overflow: auto/scroll` on a page root or a
  full-page wrapper. That produces the double-scrollbar bug (document + main).
  The only viewport-height owner is `.app`.
- **Bounded internal scroll is allowed for a region, not the page.** If a region
  inside a card must scroll independently (long list, log, etc.), scroll that
  inner region with the **Card scroll standard** below (8px bar, 4px insets) —
  don't make the page scroll to accommodate it.
- **Cards/panels** on a page use the shared `.panel`/`.hero` contract: 16px
  padding, radius tokens, and the card-scroll standard when they scroll. Reuse
  existing widgets; don't restyle them per page.
- **No page-local header or footer** — those come from `AppShell`.
- **Top spacing** is owned by the shell's `--page-gap` (see design-system "Page
  top spacing rule"); don't add ad-hoc top margins to push content off the
  header.

If a new page seems to *need* its own page-level scroll or a viewport height,
that's a signal to revisit this contract rather than override it — flag it.

## Header responsive behavior

The header (`.site-header`) is `position: sticky; top: 0` on every viewport.
`.site-header-inner` is a CSS grid with two layouts:

- **Default (mobile + tablet, `< 1200px`)** — two rows:
  `"brand account"` / `"nav nav"`. Nav is left-aligned on its own row.
- **Desktop single bar (`≥ 1200px`)** —
  `grid-template-columns: minmax(max-content, 1fr) auto minmax(max-content, 1fr)`,
  areas `"brand nav account"`. The `max-content` side tracks reserve the
  brand's/account's real width so the centered nav **slides right rather than
  overlapping the wordmark**, and the bar falls back to the two-row layout once
  the single row can no longer fit. If you change brand/nav width, re-verify
  this `1200px` threshold (it's tuned, not arbitrary).

UX intent: nav stays visually centered while there is room, degrades
gracefully (shift, then stack) — it must never collide or clip.

## Home cards — scroll behavior per viewport

The deck is `.home-grid` → `.home-grid__track` → three `.home-slide`s
(`--about` / `--market` / `--watch`). Scrolling differs by viewport **on
purpose**; keep these distinctions:

- **Desktop (`≥ 1024px`)** — full-height dashboard. Three columns on one row
  (Market 1–3 · About 4–9 · Watch 10–12). Each card fills the viewport height
  and shrinks with it. The **page never scrolls**; instead a card's own content
  scrolls *inside* it only when the viewport is too short. The card (`.hero` /
  `.panel`) is a fixed-height shell with `overflow: hidden`; an **inner region**
  scrolls (`.hero-body`, `.flow-steps`, `.watchlist-items`) via `overflow:
  hidden auto` + `scrollbar-gutter: stable`. The hero scrolls as one body
  (`.hero-body` wrapper); panels keep their head/intro/form fixed and scroll
  only the list.

### Card padding & scrollbar placement (matches Figma)

Applies to **every card app-wide** (`.panel` and `.hero`), not just the home
deck.

- **16px padding on all sides** of every card, all viewports, so content
  breathes — baked into the base `.panel` rule (`padding: 1rem`) and `.hero`.
  Don't re-set card padding per page/breakpoint.
- When a region scrolls **inside** a card, it gets the **card scroll standard**:
  an **8px bar parked 4px from the card edge with 4px between the bar and
  content** (4 + 8 + 4 = the 16px right inset). This is a **desktop effect**
  (the breakpoint where the region actually scrolls); mobile/tablet decks scroll
  at the page level, not inside cards.
  - Appearance (the 8px rounded bar) is shared once in the **"Card scroll
    standard"** block in `index.css` — grouped over `.hero-body`, `.flow-steps`,
    `.watchlist-items`, `.strategy-list`. Firefox uses `scrollbar-width: thin`.
  - Positioning is per-region at the breakpoint where it scrolls:
    `overflow: hidden auto; margin-right: -12px; padding-right: 4px;
    scrollbar-gutter: stable;`. The negative margin pulls the scroll box into
    the card's 16px padding so the bar lands 4px from the edge; `padding-right`
    re-opens the 4px gap to content; `scrollbar-gutter` keeps it stable.
  - **Never put the scroll on the padded card itself** (the bar would sit far
    inside the padding) — always scroll an inner region with this inset.
- **Adding a new scrollable card region:** add its selector to the "Card scroll
  standard" group (for the 8px bar) and give it the inset above in the
  breakpoint where it scrolls. Keep the card's own padding at 16px.
- **Tablet (`768–1199px`)** — About full-width top row; Market + Watch
  side-by-side below. Cards are **content-height and never scroll internally**;
  the page (`.app-main`) scrolls vertically.
- **Mobile (`< 768px`)** — Embla horizontal **swipe deck** (one card per
  screen), driven by the sticky `.home-tabs-shell` tabs. Cards are
  content-height and **must not scroll internally**; the deck (`.home-grid`)
  owns vertical scroll while `.app-main` is locked (`overflow: hidden`). Embla
  owns horizontal swipes (`touch-action: pan-y`). The tab bar full-bleeds to
  the viewport edges (`margin-inline: calc(var(--content-pad) * -1)`) with a
  full-width bottom border.

Rule of thumb: **content scrolls inside the card only on desktop**. On
tablet/mobile the card grows to its content and the surrounding region scrolls.

## Responsive breakpoints (reference)

- `< 768px` — mobile
- `768px` — tablet layout begins
- `1024px` — desktop **card** dashboard (3-col, internal scroll)
- `1200px` — desktop **header** single bar (independent of the card breakpoint)
